{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Content-addressed snapshot cache + background janitor\n\n## Why\n\nThe same SHA is often requested by multiple concurrent gates; re-materializing identical\ncontent per call is wasteful. An immutable SHA is a perfect cache key (no staleness), so\n`<cache>/<sha>/` is content-addressed. The hard part is RECLAMATION under disk pressure\nwithout corrupting concurrent readers — the spike showed our original PID+heartbeat lease is\nunsound (cannot represent N readers; PID reuse; crash-stale). Use kernel guarantees instead,\nmirroring Gitaly / Sourcegraph gitserver / Bazel / ccache.\n\n## What\n\n- Cache entries keyed by SHA, populated via S1's atomic dir-rename; single-flight per SHA\n  (in-process lock/future + optional cross-process `flock(LOCK_EX)` on `locks/<sha>`).\n- Reader safety via POSIX delete-on-last-close: readers `open()` files up front; evicting an\n  entry under an open fd is harmless; `ENOENT`/`EIO`/short-read -> treat as miss -> re-materialize.\n- LRU recency via mtime TOUCHED-ON-READ (never `atime`; broken under relatime/noatime).\n- Single background janitor in the server (off the hot path): primary trigger = FREE-SPACE\n  watermark (`shutil.disk_usage`), backstopped by an incrementally-maintained byte total\n  (no hot-path `du`); secondary max-age trim for cold entries.\n- Eviction mechanism: `rename(<sha>, trash/<uuid>)` (atomic disappearance) THEN `rmtree` the\n  trash entry — never in-place `rmtree`; skip entries within a short mtime grace window.\n- Cross-process GC interlock: exclusive `flock` on `<cache>/gc/lock` per GC pass; population\n  stays lock-free.\n- Startup sweep: `rmtree tmp/* trash/*`; reconcile byte-total with one full walk.\n- Self-heal: read-error -> discard (rename-to-trash) -> re-materialize; optional periodic\n  integrity re-verify (re-derive tree git-ids vs the directory name).\n- **Byte-total integrity:** increments (on populate, lock-free) and decrements (on evict,\n  under `gc/lock`) update the running total through a single atomic path so concurrent\n  populate-vs-evict cannot drift it (no TOCTOU); the startup full-walk is the reconciliation\n  source of truth.\n- **Trash ownership:** a `rename-to-trash` whose `rmtree` is interrupted leaves a straggler\n  the janitor re-drains on its next pass (not only at startup), so trash cannot accumulate\n  unboundedly within a long-running process.\n- **Tunables are CONFIGURABLE with documented defaults** (per-deployment/disk-size): the\n  free-space watermark, the mtime grace window, the max-age cold-trim cutoff, and the optional\n  integrity-reverify period.\n- **ADR:** capture the cache architecture (content-addressed layout, delete-on-last-close\n  reader safety, flock GC interlock) AND the rejected PID+heartbeat lease (the spike outcome).\n\n## Scope\n\n- In: the SHA-keyed cache, single-flight, the janitor (trigger/policy/mechanism/interlock),\n  byte-total integrity, trash drain, configurable tunables, startup sweep, self-heal, the ADR.\n- Out: materialization itself (S1); verdict memoization (deferred fast-follow).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Two concurrent gates requesting the same SHA trigger exactly one materialization\n      (single-flight); the second reads the shared entry.\n- [ ] Evicting an entry while a reader holds it open does not disrupt the in-flight read\n      (delete-on-last-close); new lookups cleanly miss and re-materialize.\n- [ ] The janitor reclaims under a free-space watermark using LRU by touch-on-read mtime\n      (NOT atime), skipping entries within the grace window; runs off the hot path.\n- [ ] The secondary max-age cold-trim evicts genuinely cold entries (covered by its own test).\n- [ ] Startup sweep clears `tmp/*` and `trash/*` and reconciles the byte total via one full walk.\n- [ ] The incrementally-maintained byte total stays consistent under concurrent populate\n      (lock-free) and evict (under `gc/lock`) — no TOCTOU drift; verified against the full walk.\n- [ ] An interrupted `rename-to-trash`/`rmtree` straggler is re-drained on a later janitor pass.\n- [ ] Eviction is rename-to-trash then rmtree; no in-place recursive delete of a live entry.\n- [ ] A second process cannot run a GC pass concurrently (exclusive `gc/lock`); population\n      remains lock-free.\n- [ ] No PID/heartbeat lease is used; liveness rests on fds/flock, not PID liveness.\n- [ ] A corrupt/truncated entry is detected on read-error and self-healed by re-materialization.\n- [ ] The watermark, grace window, max-age cutoff, and reverify period are configurable with\n      documented defaults.\n- [ ] An ADR records the cache/janitor architecture and the rejected PID+heartbeat lease."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782526443487914001,"uuid":"3cbf1e9c-71e2-410c-8d48-fe24f7dfabed"}